{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628744"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:00:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17237"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17237"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77602"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9927"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63115"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7649"},{"type":"tags","id":"10697"},{"type":"tags","id":"10707"},{"type":"tags","id":"10710"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23277"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23281"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77602"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECopy number variants represent a significant form of structural variation in the human genome, affecting gene dosage and phenotypic expression.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes copy number variants?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Changes in DNA methylation patterns","Inversions of DNA sequences","Changes in single DNA base pairs","Exchange of DNA between chromosomes","Segments of DNA that are duplicated or deleted"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESegments of DNA that are duplicated or deleted\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes copy number variants (CNVs). These structural variations involve changes in the number of copies of DNA segments compared to a reference genome. CNVs can range from 1 kilobase to several megabases in size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanges in DNA methylation patterns\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes epigenetic modifications rather than structural variants\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInversions of DNA sequences\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a different type of structural variant where DNA sequence is reversed in orientation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanges in single DNA base pairs\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes single nucleotide variants or polymorphisms, not CNVs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExchange of DNA between chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes chromosomal translocations, not CNVs\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECopy number variants can affect gene dosage and contribute to both normal phenotypic variation and disease states. Common examples include CNVs associated with neurodevelopmental conditions such as autism spectrum disorders and schizophrenia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Copy number variants are structural variations where segments of DNA are duplicated or deleted compared to a reference genome.","Copy number variants can range from 1 kilobase to several megabases in size.","Copy number variants contribute to both normal genetic variation and disease phenotypes in humans."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Vicari S, Napoli E, Cordeddu V, Menghini D, Alesi V, 